{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17493052","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17493052"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:54:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1208"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1208"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.05,0.68,0.03,0.07]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55941"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1208"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1208"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41490"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"166"},{"type":"tags","id":"934"},{"type":"tags","id":"1534"},{"type":"tags","id":"2118"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1424"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1571"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1572"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12283"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14557"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43838"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55941","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55941"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a five-day history of severe abdominal pain and bloody diarrhoea. She reports having approximately ten loose bloody bowel actions per day, diffuse abdominal pain, and increasing abdominal distension. She has a medical history of ulcerative colitis diagnosed ten years ago. Her medications include oral sulfasalazine. She does not take any other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell with a pulse rate of 100/min, blood pressure 110/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, temperature 38.3\u00b0C, and SpO2 98% on room air. Her abdomen is distended and diffusely tender without guarding or rigidity. Bowel sounds are reduced.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInvestigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 15 \u00a0x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 105 g/L (115-165)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EC-reactive protein: 60 mg/L (\u0026lt;5)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn abdominal X-ray shows widespread large bowel thickening which measures 6 cm in diameter at the transverse colon and no pneumoperitoneum.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Colectomy","Rectal mesalazine","Intravenous corticosteroids","Intravenous cyclosporin","Infliximab"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes a severe flare of ulcerative colitis (UC) with features concerning for developing toxic megacolon. The patient\u0027s presentation with severe abdominal pain, frequent bloody diarrhoea, abdominal distension, tachycardia, fever, and leukocytosis are concerning for this life-threatening complication. The abdominal X-ray showing a borderline dilated transverse colon (greater than 6 cm is consistent with megacolon) further supports this diagnosis. The most appropriate initial management is \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIntravenous corticosteroids are the first-line treatment for severe UC flares, including early toxic megacolon. They help to rapidly reduce inflammation and can potentially prevent progression to fulminant toxic megacolon. It\u0027s crucial to start this treatment promptly while simultaneously involving gastroenterology and surgical teams for close monitoring and potential escalation of care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecolectomy\u003C/strong\u003E may ultimately be necessary if the patient doesn\u0027t respond to medical management or if there are signs of perforation, progressive dilatation or worsening toxicity. However, it\u0027s not the initial step in management unless there are absolute indications for immediate surgery (such as perforation or uncontrolled haemorrhage).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERectal mesalazine\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for managing a severe UC flare, especially with features of toxic megacolon. It\u0027s more appropriate for mild to moderate distal colitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous cyclosporin\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Einfliximab\u003C/strong\u003E are potential rescue therapies if the patient fails to respond adequately to intravenous corticosteroids after 3-5 days. They are not first-line treatments in this acute, severe presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of this patient should also include fluid resuscitation, electrolyte correction and bowel rest. Close monitoring for signs of clinical deterioration or colonic perforation is essential.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Toxic megacolon is a severe complication of ulcerative colitis characterized by colonic dilatation, systemic toxicity, and risk of perforation.","IV steroids are the first-line treatment for severe ulcerative colitis flares, including early toxic megacolon, before considering rescue therapies or surgery.","Early involvement of gastroenterology and surgical teams is crucial in managing severe ulcerative colitis flares with potential toxic megacolon."],"references":["Gibson P, Iser J. Inflammatory Bowel Disease. Australian Family Physician. 2005;34(4):233 - 237. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afpbackissues/2005/200504/200504gibson.pdf","Botoman VA, Bonner GF, Botoman DA. Management of inflammatory bowel disease. Am Fam Physician. 1998;57(1):57-68, 71-2. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/afp/1998/0101/p57.html","Nordenholtz KE, Stowe SP, Stormont JM, Stowe MM, Chessin LN, Shah AN, et al. The cause of death in inflammatory bowel disease: a comparison of death certificates and hospital charts in Rochester, New York. Am J Gastroenterol. 1995;90(6):927-32. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/7771423/","Inflammatory Bowel Disease. In: Therapeutic Guidelines Ltd [online]  2020. Available at: https://www.tg.org.au","Desai J, Elnaggar M, Hanfy AA, Doshi R. Toxic Megacolon: Background, Pathophysiology, Management Challenges and Solutions. Clin Exp Gastroenterol. 2020 May 19;13:203-210. Available at: https://doi.org/10.2147/CEG.S200760"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41490"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1208"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41490","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41490"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T19:35:44+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T19:35:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1208"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55941"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"rela